<h2>Tata Trust Chairman Ratan Tata and Tata Sons pledged Rs 1,500 crore to aid the nation in its fight against the coronavirus pandemic    </h2>
</div>
<style type="text/css">
  .rtecenter {text-align: center;}.rteright {text-align: right;}
  ._telegramicon { background:url(https://imgk.timesnownews.com/s/v1/img/d_telegram.png) no-repeat 0 0 !important  }
    ._whatappicon { background:url(https://imgk.timesnownews.com/s/v1/img/d_whatappicon.svg) no-repeat 0 0 !important  }
</style>
<div class="check-point clear-fix" percent="40%"></div>

<div class="consumption-artical">
<div class="artical-description">
<div class="component_9" style="width:600px;">
<div class="img-pod" id="articleImg_570727">
<img alt="Tata Trusts" class="lazy-image" data-src="https://imgk.timesnownews.com/story/TATAMISTRY.jpg?tr=w-600,h-450,fo-auto" id="article_img_570727" src="https://iks.timesnownews.com/s/v1/img/c_tnplaceholder.png?tr=w-600,h-450" title="Tata Trusts"/>
<div class="content creditphoto">
        Tata Trusts pledges Rs 500 crore to combat coronavirus  | &amp;nbspPhoto Credit:&amp;nbspBCCL      </div>
</div>
</div>
<p><strong>New Delhi:</strong> Ratan Tata and Tata Sons, on Friday, pledged a generous Rs 1,500 crores to aid the nation in combatting the COVID-19 pandemic. </p>
<p>Tata Trusts which is helmed by Ratan Tata committed Rs 500 crore and Tata Sons, the principal holding company of the salt-to-software conglomerate, announced another Rs 1,000 crores to manufacture ventilators, protective gear, Covid-19 testing kits and facilities to treat infected persons.    </p>
<p>The development comes at a time where the nation is reeling under the dual crises of coronavirus outbreak and lockdown to curb its transmission. </p>
<p>The funds will be utilised for Personal Protective Equipment for medical personnel on the frontlines of the outbreak, respiratory systems for treating increasing cases, kits to increase per capita testing, setting up modular treatment facilities for infected patients among others.</p>
<p>"The COVID 19 crisis is one of the toughest challenges we will face as a race. The Tata Trusts and the Tata group companies have in the past risen to the needs of the nation. At this moment, the need of the hour is greater than any other time," Ratan Tata, Chairman said in a statement on Twitter today.</p>
<div class="media_embed">
<blockquote class="twitter-tweet" height="" width="">
<p dir="ltr" lang="en">The COVID 19 crisis is one of the toughest challenges we will face as a race. The Tata Trusts and the Tata group companies have in the past risen to the needs of the nation. At this moment, the need of the hour is greater than any other time. <a href="https://t.co/y6jzHxUafM" rel="nofollow">pic.twitter.com/y6jzHxUafM</a></p>
— Ratan N. Tata (@RNTata2000) <a href="https://twitter.com/RNTata2000/status/1243852348637605888?ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw" rel="nofollow">March 28, 2020</a></blockquote>
<script async="" charset="utf-8" height="" src="https://platform.twitter.com/widgets.js" width=""></script></div>
<p>"In this exceptionally difficult period, I believe that urgent emergency resources need to be deployed to cope with the needs of fighting the COVID 19 crisis, which is one of the toughest challenges the human race will face. Today, The Tata Trusts continue their pledge to protect and empower all affected communities and is committing Rs 500 crore... " he added.</p>
<p>He said that Tata Sons and the Tata group companies are joined by committed local and global partners as well as the government to fight this crisis on a united public health collaboration platform which will strive to reach out to sections that are underprivileged and deprived.</p>
<p>N Chandrasekaran, the Chairman of Tata Sons, in a statement said, "in addition to the initiatives articulated by Tata Trusts, we are also bringing in the ventilators necessary and are gearing up to also manufacture the same soon in India".</p>
<p>The country is facing an unprecedented situation and crisis. All of us would have to do whatever it takes to alleviate and enhance the quality of lives of the communities we serve, he added.</p>
